</gallery>

The explosion-bent fore mast of ''Maine'' is located at the [[United States Naval Academy]] at [[Annapolis, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/ussmaine.htm | title = U.S.S. Maine Memorial, Arlington National Cemetery }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.netitor.com/photos/schools/navy/sports/m-crew/auto_pdf/crewmg.pdf|page=11 | title = 2001 Navy crew media guide | accessdate =8 April 2010 }}</ref>

In 1926, the Cuban government erected a memorial to the victims of ''Maine'' on the [[Malecon, Havana|Malecon]], near the [[Hotel Nacional de Cuba|Hotel Nacional]], to commemorate United States assistance in acquiring Cuban independence from Spain.  The monument features two of ''Maine'''s four 10-inch guns.   In 1961, the memorial was damaged by crowds, following the [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]], and the eagle on top was broken and removed.<ref name="Baker" /> The Communist government then added its own inscription blaming "imperialist voracity in its eagerness to seize the island of Cuba" for ''Maine''{{'}}s sinking.<ref name="Baker" /><ref>''The Rough Guide to Cuba'' {{ISBN|978-1-84353-811-0}} p. 159</ref> The monument was cleaned and restored in 2013. However, the eagle's head was retained by the U.S. Interests Section in Havana, and the body by the city's museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/havana-restores-monument-victims-uss-maine-091350756.html|title=Havana restores monument to victims of USS Maine|date=16 February 2013|work=Yahoo News}}</ref>

