=== Other memorials ===

* In 1898, [[Georges Méliès]] made his movie, [[Divers At Work on the Wreck of The Maine (film)|''Visite sous-marine du Maine'']], about rescuers freeing bodies from the sunken ''Maine''.
* In 1914, one of ''Maine''{{'}}s six anchors was taken from the [[Washington Navy Yard]] to City Park in [[Reading, Pennsylvania]], and dedicated during a ceremony presided over by [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], who was then assistant secretary of the navy.<ref>{{cite news | last = Cuyler | first = Greta | title = Group recalls dedication of anchor from U.S. warship in Reading's City Park | newspaper = Reading Eagle | date = 11 August 2008 | url = http://readingeagle.com/article.aspx?id=101544 | accessdate =8 April 2010 }}</ref>
* A brass torpedo tube hatch recovered from ''Maine'' is on display at Lakeside Park in Oakland, California. It was stolen from its mount in the park in May 2011, but quickly recovered by authorities after the thieves attempted to sell it for scrap metal. The large piece was relocated and mounted by OPW Facility Services in front of Oakland's Veterans building on Grand Ave.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2011/05/16/oakland-thieves-make-off-with-relic-from-uss-maine/ | title = Oakland Thieves Make Off With Relic From USS Maine | publisher = CBS Local Media|work= SanFrancisco.CBSlocal.com | date = 16 May 2011 | accessdate =2 October 2011 }}</ref>
* [[Battleship Maine Monument|A memorial]] including the shield and scrollwork from the bow of the ship is located in [[Bangor, Maine]].
* A 6-inch gun from ''Maine'' is in [[Washington, DC]] at the [[National Museum of the United States Navy]].
* A 6-inch gun from ''Maine'' is in [[Fort Allen Park]] in [[Portland, Maine]].
* A 6-inch gun from ''Maine'' is displayed on the front lawn of city hall in [[Alpena, Michigan]], as well as a bronze plaque made from the vessel.
* The base of ''Maine''{{'}}s conning tower is currently on display at Westbrook Veterans' Memorial Park in [[Canton, Ohio]], hometown of President McKinley.
* Shells from the main battery were placed along with small plaques as memorials at the Soldier's Home in [[Marion, Indiana]], (now a [[VA hospital]] and national cemetery), at the St. Joseph County Courthouse lawn in [[South Bend, Indiana]], at [[Point Defiance Park]] in [[Tacoma, Washington]] and at the [[old soldiers' home]] in [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota. A shell from the main battery is located just inside of the Pine St. entrance of city hall in [[Lewiston, Maine]].{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}{{importance inline}}
* A monument for ''Maine'' with a portion of a bronze engine room ventilator shaft is located in [[Pompton Lakes, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pomptonlakesgov.com/229/USS-Battleship-Maine | title = USS Battleship Maine | publisher = Borough of Pompton Lakes, N.J. | accessdate =16 June 2017 }}</ref>
* The capstan of the ship was secured for [[Charleston, South Carolina]] where it was displayed on the Battery until 2006; it is currently awaiting reinstallation.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper = The Evening Post (Charleston, SC) | title = Maine Relics Are Here | date = 11 September 1913 }}</ref>
* A shell from the ''Maine'' is on display at the Hoboken Public Library in [[Hoboken, New Jersey]].{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}{{importance inline}}
* There is a plaque dedicated to ''Maine'' at the war memorial in Stephen R. Gregg Park in [[Bayonne, New Jersey]]. The plaque is made from metal salvaged from the ship.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Coughlin | first1 = Bill | year = 2012 | title = U.S.S. Maine Memorial Marker. | publisher = Bill Coughlin | url =http://www.hmdb.org//marker.asp?MarkerID=54632 | accessdate =25 July 2014 | ref = Coughlin, Bill. "U.S.S. Maine Memorial Marker." U.S.S. Maine Memorial Marker. Bill Coughlin, 19 April 2012. Web. 25 July 2014. <http://www.hmdb.org//marker.asp?MarkerID=54632>.}}</ref>
* A fragment of the ship is on display at Moraine farm, the Homestead of Col. Deeds in Kettering, Ohio. (Currently under the stewardship of Kettering Health Network).
* A six-inch gun turret of the ship is on display at VFW Post 1289 in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]. 
A 6-inch deck gun from ''Maine'' is on the North lawn of the South Carolina State House in Columbia, SC.

A bronze torpedo tube and armoured hatch form part of a memorial in West Park, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, just south of West North Avenue, http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM769B_Maine_Memorial_Pittsburgh_PA

There is also a U.S.S. Maine Memorial plaque<visible in photographs and physically in situ> at the south door of the Jefferson County Courthouse, in Steubenville, OH.

{{Coord|23.198|-82.355|format=dms |display=title|name=USS Maine|type:landmark_dim:100m_scale:90000_region:CU-02 }}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.se/~pa/mar/ussmaine.htm |title= Discovery of USS Maine |date= July 2003|website=Nordic Underwater Archaeology |accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref>

