{{Other uses|Women and children first (disambiguation)}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}

[[File:Wreck of the Birkenhead.jpg|thumb|upright|right|250px|Soldiers stand fast on the deck of {{HMS|Birkenhead|1845|6}} while women and children head off in a lifeboat, as depicted in [[Charles Napier Hemy|Thomas Hemy's]] painting "The Wreck of the ''Birkenhead''" ({{Circa|1892}}).]]

"'''Women and children first'''" (or to a lesser extent, the '''Birkenhead Drill''')<ref>{{cite book|title=Collected Verse of Rudyard Kipling|author=Rudyard Kipling|year=2005|isbn=1-4179-0750-9|publisher=Kessinger|url=https://books.google.com/?id=76QI2lskupEC|page=305}}</ref>{{sfn|Heinlein|1978|p=169}} is a code of conduct dating from 1852, whereby the lives of women and children were to be saved first in a life-threatening situation, typically abandoning ship, when survival resources such as [[lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboat]]s were limited.

While the phrase first appeared in the 1860 novel ''Harrington: A Story of True Love'', by William Douglas O'Connor,<ref>{{cite web  | last =  | first =  | authorlink =  | coauthors =  | title = Women and Children First  | work =  | publisher = The Phrase Finder  | date =  | url = http://www.phrases.org.uk/meanings/women-and-children-first.html  | doi =  | accessdate = 2010-04-16 }}</ref><ref>[{{Google books|plainurl=y|id= sgU3wxdI08cC|text=women and children first|page=187}} O’Connor (1860), pp. 187-188]</ref> the first documented application of "women and children first" was in May 1840 when, after a lightning-strike, fire broke out aboard the American packet ''Poland'' en route from New York to Le Havre. According to a passenger, J.H. Buckingham of Boston:

"... the captain said that he had little doubt that the ship was on fire, and that we must endeavor to get at it. On a suggestion that we might be obliged to take to the boats, it was immediately remarked by one of our French passengers, and responded to by others - 'Let us take care of the women and children first.'" <ref>Howland, Southworth Allen:Steamboat Disasters and Railroad Accidents in the United States (2nd edition) Worcester,1840: p.306</ref>

This led to a precautionary evacuation of women, children and a few male passengers into the longboat while the other male passengers and crew remained aboard to fight the blaze.<ref>''The Times''(London) 27 June 1840, p.6; reprinting a report dated 29 May 1840, first appearing in the ''Boston Courier''.</ref> As Buckingham was a journalist his vivid account of the incident was published first in the ''Boston Courier'', picked up by other papers including ''The Times'' (London) and also reprinted in a book published in the same year<ref>Howland, Southworth Allen:Steamboat Disasters and Railroad Accidents in the United States (2nd edition) Worcester,1840: p.306</ref>, thus gaining wide currency.

A more noted instance occurred during the 1852 evacuation of the [[Royal Navy]] troopship {{HMS|Birkenhead|1845|6}}.<ref name="Birkenhead"/> It is, however, most famously associated with the [[sinking of the RMS Titanic|sinking of RMS ''Titanic'']] in 1912.

As a code of conduct, "women and children first" has no basis in [[maritime law]]. According to disaster evacuation expert Ed Galea, in modern-day evacuations people will usually "help the most vulnerable to leave the scene first, likely to be the injured, elderly and young children."{{sfn|Castella|2012}}

In the [[Boy Scouts of America]]'s [[Sea Scouting (Boy Scouts of America)|Sea Scouting]] program, "Women and children first" is considered "the motto of the sea."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.scoutingmagazine.org/2014/01/27/amid-one-oath-one-law-changes-the-sea-scout-promise-is-here-to-stay/|title=Amid 'One Oath, One Law' changes, the Sea Scout promise is here to stay - Bryan on Scouting|date=2014-01-27|work=Bryan on Scouting|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en-US}}</ref>

== History ==
===19th century===
[[File:WilliamDouglasOConnor byRitz and Hastings.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Novelist William Douglas O'Connor]]

A well known appearance of the phrase "women and children first" occurred in the 1860 novel ''Harrington: A Story of True Love'', during the recounting of the death of Captain Harrington, the father of the [[eponymous]] character John Harrington.{{cn|date=May 2016}} Captain Harrington’s fictional death illustrates not only the concept of "women and children first" but also that of [[The captain goes down with the ship|"the captain goes down with his ship"]].

{{bquote|"Back from the boats," [Captain Harrington] shouts, catchin' up the hand-spike. "The first man that touches a boat I'll brain. Women and children first, men."...
"Timbs," says he, "give my love to my wife and boy, if I never see 'em again. God bless ye, men."...

[Captain Eldad] paused, wiping away with his sleeve the salt tears which the simple epic of a brave man's death brought to his eyes.
"That was the story, and them was the last words Timbs brought home to your mother ... An' that's the way he died. Women and children saved. That's a comfort...But he died...

"It was a manly way to leave the world," [John Harrington] said. "Life is sweet to me with the memory of such a father."
|author=William Douglas O'Connor
|source=''Harrington: A Story of True Love'' (1860) 
|pages=188-189
|accessdate=3 June 2013]. 
}}

During the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, ships typically did not carry enough lifeboats to save all the passengers and crew in the event of disaster. In 1870, answering a question at the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]] about the sinking of the [[paddle steamer]] [[PS Normandy|''Normandy'']], [[George Shaw-Lefevre, 1st Baron Eversley|George Shaw-Lefevre]] said that,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=vs8MAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA323 The Parliamentary debates (Authorized edition), Volume 200, 21 March 1870, pp. 323–324] H. M. Stationery Office, 1870</ref>

{{quote|In the opinion of the [[Board of Trade]], it will not be possible to compel the passenger steamers running between England and France to have boats sufficient for the very numerous passengers they often carry. They would encumber the decks, and rather add to the danger than detract from it.}}

The practice of women and children first arose from the actions of soldiers during the sinking of the [[Royal Navy]] troopship {{HMS|Birkenhead|1845|6}} in 1852 after it struck rocks.<ref name="Birkenhead">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-16576289 "Costa Concordia: The rules of evacuating a ship"]. BBC. Retrieved 15 June 2017</ref> Captain Robert Salmond RN ordered Colonel Seton to send men to the [[chain pump]]s; sixty were directed to this task, sixty more were assigned to the [[block and tackle|tackles]] of the lifeboats, and the rest were assembled on the [[poop deck]] in order to raise the forward part of the ship.<ref>{{cite book|title=Our Soldiers: Gallant Deeds of the British Army during Victoria's Reign|last=Kingston|first=William Henry Giles|year=1899|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/23052|publisher=Nick Hodson|location=London}}</ref> The women and children were placed in the ship's [[cutter (ship)|cutter]], which lay alongside.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Wreck of HM Steamer "Birkenhead" – 26 Feb 1852|url=http://capeinfo.com/more/myths-legends-a-old-folks-stories/568-the-wreck-of-hm-steamer-qbirkenheadq-26-feb-1852 |publisher=Capeinfo |accessdate=12 May 2013}}</ref> The sinking was memorialized in newspapers and paintings of the time, and in poems such as [[Rudyard Kipling]]'s 1893 "Soldier an' Sailor Too".

===20th century===
By the turn of the 20th century, larger ships meant more people could travel, but regulations were generally still insufficient to provide for all passengers: for example British legislation concerning the number of lifeboats was based on the tonnage of a vessel and only encompassed vessels of "10,000 [[Gross_register_tonnage|gross tons]] and over". The result was that a sinking usually involved a moral dilemma for passengers and crew as to [[Lifeboat ethics|whose lives should be saved]] with the limited available lifeboats.

[[File:Titanic-lifeboat.gif|thumb|right|RMS ''Titanic'' survivors aboard a collapsible lifeboat]]

The phrase was popularised by its usage on the {{RMS|Titanic}}.{{sfn|Marshall|2004|p=?}}{{page needed|date=May 2013}}  The [[Charles Lightoller|Second Officer]] suggested to [[Edward Smith (sea captain)|Captain Smith]], "Hadn't we better get the women and children into the boats, sir?", to which the captain responded: "put the women and children in and lower away".{{sfn|Lord|2005|p=37}}  The First (Officer Murdoch) and Second (Officer Lightoller) officers interpreted the evacuation order differently; Murdoch took it to mean women and children ''first'', while Lightoller took it to mean women and children ''only''. Second Officer Lightoller lowered lifeboats with empty seats if there were no women and children waiting to board, while First Officer Murdoch allowed a limited number of men to board if all the nearby women and children had embarked.{{sfn|Barczewski|2006|p=21}}  As a consequence, 74% of the women and 52% of the children on board were saved, but only 20% of the men.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anesi.com/titanic.htm |title=Titanic Casualty Figures |first=Chuck |last=Anesi}}</ref>  Some officers on the ''Titanic'' misinterpreted the order from Captain Smith, and tried to prevent men from boarding the lifeboats.{{sfn|Lord|1997|p=63}}{{sfn|Ballard|1987|p=87}} It was intended that women and children would board first, with any remaining free spaces for men. Because not all women and children were saved on the ''Titanic'', the few men who survived, like [[White Star Line|White Star]] official [[J. Bruce Ismay]], were initially branded as cowards.{{sfn|Benedict|Gardner|2000|page=204}}

===21st century===
There is no legal basis for the protocol of women and children first in international [[maritime law]].

A more recent application of "women and children first" occurred in March 2011, when a [[floating restaurant]] in [[Covington, Kentucky]], tore from its moorings, stranding 83 people on the [[Ohio River]]. Women were rescued first; there were no casualties of either sex.<ref name="ap20110313">{{cite news | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=6209508&campaign=rss&source=ESPNHeadlines | title=Cris Collinsworth among 83 rescued | publisher=[[ESPN]] | date=2011-03-13 | agency=Associated Press | accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref>

